data.name: call_type
data.description: one of the following strings: (filterable: call_type) mt_call - Outgoing Call  mo_call - Incoming Call  mo_miss - Missed Incoming Call

data.name: created_on
data.description: when the call was received or sent (datetime) (filterable: before and after)

data.name: duration
data.description: the duration of the call in seconds (int, 0 for missed calls)

data.name: phone
data.description: the phone number of the caller or callee depending on the call_type (string) (filterable: phone)

data.name: relayer
data.description: which relayer received or placed this call (int) (filterable: relayer)

data.name: Claim Relayers
country
data.description: which country the sim card for this relayer is registered for (string, two letter country code) (filterable: country)

data.name: last_seen
data.description: the datetime when this relayer was last seen by TextIt (datetime) (filterable: before and after)

data.name: name
data.description: the name of this relayer (string)

data.name: network_type
data.description: the type of network the device is connected to as reported by Android (string)

data.name: pending_message_count
data.description: how many messages are assigned to this relayer but not yet sent (int)

data.name: phone
data.description: the phone number for the relayer (string) (filterable: phone)

data.name: power_level
data.description: the power level of the device (int)

data.name: power_source
data.description: the source of power as reported by Android (string)

data.name: power_status
data.description: the power status, either STATUS_DISCHARGING or STATUS_CHARGING (string)

data.name: relayer
data.description: the id of the the relayer (long)

A GET returns the list of Android relayers for your organization, in the order of last activity date. Note that all status information for the device is as of the last time it was seen and can be null before the first sync.
data.name: List Relayers
created_on
data.description: the datetime when this sms was either received by the relayer or created by TextIt (datetime) (filterable: before and after)

data.name: delivered_on
data.description: for outgoing messages, the datetime when the relayer delivered the message (null if not yet sent or an incoming message) (datetime)

data.name: direction
data.description: the direction of the SMS, either I for incoming messages or O for outgoing (string) (filterable: direction)

data.name: phone
data.description: the phone number of the sender or receiver, depending on direction (string) (filterable: phone)

data.name: relayer
data.description: the id of the Android relayer that sent or received this message (int) (filterable: relayer)

data.name: sent_on
data.description: for outgoing messages, the datetime when the relayer sent the message (null if not yet sent or an incoming message) (datetime)

data.name: status
data.description: the status of this message, a string one of: (filterable: status) Q - Message is queued awaiting to be sent S - Message has been sent by the relayer D - Message was delivered to the recipient H - Incoming message was handled by TextIt F - Message was not sent due to a failure

data.name: text
data.description: the text of the message received, not this is the logical view, this message may have been received as multiple text messages (string)

data.name: before

data.name: country
data.description: the country this relayer is in (string, two letter country code)

data.name: phone
data.description: the phone number of the relayer to remove (string)

description:
Easily create interactive SMS applications anywhere in the world.  At the core of TextIt lies our exclusive Flow engine. With Flows, anybody can set up or modify a complex SMS application without the need of a programmer or expensive consulting company.
Using a basic Android phone, you can launch your application instantly in any country while avoiding expensive set-up costs or external technical support.
